 &lt;/div></description></item><item><title>Imperative vs Declarative</title><link>https://cloud.layer5.io/academy/learning-paths/98e16360-a366-4b78-8e0a-031da07fdacb/sks-starter/kubernetes/content/imperative-vs-declarative/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://cloud.layer5.io/academy/learning-paths/98e16360-a366-4b78-8e0a-031da07fdacb/sks-starter/kubernetes/content/imperative-vs-declarative/</guid><description>&lt;h3 id="imperative-vs-declarative">&lt;strong>Imperative vs Declarative&lt;/strong>&lt;a class="td-heading-self-link" href="#imperative-vs-declarative" aria-label="Heading self-link">&lt;/a>&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>Kubernetes is a portable, extensible, open-source platform for managing containerized workloads and services that facilitates both automation and declarative configuration.&amp;quot;&lt;/p>
&lt;h4 id="configuration-differences">&lt;strong>Configuration Differences&lt;/strong>&lt;a class="td-heading-self-link" href="#configuration-differences" aria-label="Heading self-link">&lt;/a>&lt;/h4>
&lt;p>What a difference a configuration makes :).&lt;/p>
&lt;p>The significant change in this new IT world is that well-trained and practiced processes are outdated and useless. The imperative was the old world, you defined step-by-step guidance, and you also executed or oversaw the execution of those configuration steps. The declarative way is to determine the desired state and an intelligent system conducts and supervises the configuration and operation steps.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Features</title><link>https://cloud.layer5.io/academy/learning-paths/98e16360-a366-4b78-8e0a-031da07fdacb/sks-starter/kubernetes/content/features/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://cloud.layer5.io/academy/learning-paths/98e16360-a366-4b78-8e0a-031da07fdacb/sks-starter/kubernetes/content/features/</guid><description>&lt;h3 id="features">&lt;strong>Features&lt;/strong>&lt;a class="td-heading-self-link" href="#features" aria-label="Heading self-link">&lt;/a>&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://cloud.layer5.io/academy/98e16360-a366-4b78-8e0a-031da07fdacb/sks-starter/features.png" alt="features">&lt;/p>
&lt;h3 id="kubernetes-feature-details">&lt;strong>Kubernetes Feature Details&lt;/strong>&lt;a class="td-heading-self-link" href="#kubernetes-feature-details" aria-label="Heading self-link">&lt;/a>&lt;/h3>
&lt;h4 id="self-healing">&lt;strong>self-healing&lt;/strong>&lt;a class="td-heading-self-link" href="#self-healing" aria-label="Heading self-link">&lt;/a>&lt;/h4>
&lt;p>Kubernetes restarts containers that fail, replaces containers, kills containers that don&amp;rsquo;t respond to your user-defined health check, and doesn&amp;rsquo;t advertise them to clients until they are ready to serve.&lt;/p>
&lt;h4 id="automatic-bin-packing">&lt;strong>automatic bin packing&lt;/strong>&lt;a class="td-heading-self-link" href="#automatic-bin-packing" aria-label="Heading self-link">&lt;/a>&lt;/h4>
&lt;p>You provide Kubernetes with a cluster of nodes that it can use to run containerized tasks. You tell Kubernetes how much CPU and RAM each container needs. Kubernetes can fit containers onto your nodes to make the best use of your resources.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Positoning</title><link>https://cloud.layer5.io/academy/learning-paths/98e16360-a366-4b78-8e0a-031da07fdacb/sks-starter/kubernetes/content/positioning/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://cloud.layer5.io/academy/learning-paths/98e16360-a366-4b78-8e0a-031da07fdacb/sks-starter/kubernetes/content/positioning/</guid><description>&lt;h3 id="positoning">&lt;strong>Positoning&lt;/strong>&lt;a class="td-heading-self-link" href="#positoning" aria-label="Heading self-link">&lt;/a>&lt;/h3>
&lt;h4 id="kubernetes-is">&lt;strong>Kubernetes is &amp;hellip;&lt;/strong>&lt;a class="td-heading-self-link" href="#kubernetes-is" aria-label="Heading self-link">&lt;/a>&lt;/h4>
&lt;p>&amp;hellip; &lt;strong>providing&lt;/strong> the building blocks for creating developer and infrastructure platforms but preserves user choice and flexibility where it is essential.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&amp;hellip; &lt;strong>extensible&lt;/strong>, and lets users integrate their logging, monitoring, alerting, and many more solutions because it is not monolithic, and these solutions are optional and pluggable.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://cloud.layer5.io/academy/98e16360-a366-4b78-8e0a-031da07fdacb/sks-starter/positioning.png" alt="positioning">&lt;/p>
&lt;h4 id="kubernetes-is-not">&lt;strong>Kubernetes is NOT &amp;hellip;&lt;/strong>&lt;a class="td-heading-self-link" href="#kubernetes-is-not" aria-label="Heading self-link">&lt;/a>&lt;/h4>
&lt;p>&lt;strong>&amp;hellip; a traditional, all-inclusive PaaS system.&lt;/strong>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Kubernetes operates at the container level rather than at the hardware level. It provides some generally helpful features common to PaaS offerings, such as deployment, scaling, load balancing.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Basic Commands</title><link>https://cloud.layer5.io/academy/learning-paths/98e16360-a366-4b78-8e0a-031da07fdacb/sks-starter/kubernetes/content/basic-commands/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://cloud.layer5.io/academy/learning-paths/98e16360-a366-4b78-8e0a-031da07fdacb/sks-starter/kubernetes/content/basic-commands/</guid><description>&lt;h3 id="basic-commands">&lt;strong>Basic Commands&lt;/strong>&lt;a class="td-heading-self-link" href="#basic-commands" aria-label="Heading self-link">&lt;/a>&lt;/h3>
